## v2.8.0 (2026-04-24)

**Changed by:** Myrmidons shellcheck-warnings myrmidon swarm rebase session (2026-04-24)
**Verification:** verified-ci (all PRs merged, main CI green at 333b40d)

### What changed
- Added 3 new "When to Use" conditions: .claude/worktrees agent rebase, detached HEAD → branch -f fix, CHANGELOG take-HEAD strategy
- Added `### Phase 3.5a: Rebase Branches in .claude/worktrees/agent-* Paths` subsection with:
  - `git -C <worktree>` rebase pattern
  - `git branch -f <branch> HEAD` for detached HEAD recovery
  - Dependency ordering for hot-file overlapping PRs
  - CHANGELOG.md conflict strategy (always take HEAD/main)
  - Conflict resolution: take HEAD as base, add only genuinely new items
- Added 4 new Failed Attempts rows:
  - Running rebase from repo root for .claude/worktrees agent branch
  - `git checkout <ref> -- <path>` during rebase blocked by Safety Net inside worktrees
  - `git push --force` blocked; use force-with-lease with explicit refspec
  - Merging CHANGELOG conflicts during individual PR rebase causes spiraling conflicts
- Added Myrmidons to Verified On table
- Updated description to add conditions 20-22
- Bumped version 2.7.0 → 2.8.0

### Why
Myrmidons shellcheck-warnings swarm (2026-04-24) used myrmidon sub-agents that created branches
inside `.claude/worktrees/agent-<id>/` paths. Rebasing these required `git -C <path>` pattern.
After rebase, worktrees ended in detached HEAD because they were created from remote refs without
a local branch — `git branch -f <branch> HEAD` reattaches cleanly. CHANGELOG conflicts are
ubiquitous in swarm sessions; the take-HEAD strategy prevents spiraling conflicts in subsequent PRs.

