## v2.4.0 (2026-04-23)

**Changed by:** ProjectKeystone 14-PR rebase wave — ADR-disabled targets, gitleaks curl pattern, PR #329 empty-commit recovery
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed
- Added `(13)` and `(14)` trigger conditions to description: stale unlinked worktrees from a previous session; rebase "succeeds" but branch tip equals main HEAD (silent empty-commit drop)
- Added 2 new "When to Use" bullets for both trigger conditions
- Added 3 new Failed Attempts rows: `git worktree remove --force` blocked by Safety Net; rebase --continue silently dropping commit as empty when resolution matches HEAD; `--force-with-lease` failing from detached HEAD in worktree
- Added 2 new conflict resolution patterns to Phase 5: CMakeLists.txt ADR conflicts (PR adds source files, main disables test sources); security-scan.yml gitleaks conflict (PR wants action, main uses curl)
- Added both patterns to the Phase 5 conflict resolution table
- Added Safety Net workaround entry for `git worktree remove --force`
- Added ProjectKeystone to Verified On table
- Added 14-PR scale reference to Session Scale Reference table

### Why
Rebasing 14 open PRs in ProjectKeystone after a major ADR (library extraction) disabled many CMakeLists.txt test targets. Key discoveries: (1) stale /tmp worktrees from a prior session may already be unlinked in git — no `git worktree remove` needed; (2) a successful rebase can silently drop a commit as empty when the conflict resolution makes the file identical to HEAD — always verify with `git log --oneline origin/main..HEAD`; (3) `--force-with-lease` doesn't work from detached HEAD — use `git push origin "+HEAD:branch"` instead. The empty-commit drop was caught on PR #329, recovered by checking out the original SHA and rebasing again.

---

## v2.3.0 (2026-04-23)

**Changed by:** AchaeanFleet CI repair session — ~20 open PRs, rapidly advancing main via auto-merge
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed
- Added `(12)` trigger to description: "main is advancing rapidly via auto-merge during rebase session"
- Added new "When to Use" bullet for continuously-advancing main scenario
- Added Phase 14: Continuously-Advancing Main (Rebase Loop Until Stable) — full loop script with `git checkout -B` pattern, subsumption detection, and `git show origin/main:path > path` technique
- Renamed old Phase 14 to Phase 15 (Post-Rebase Verification)
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts rows: single-wave assumption failure; `git checkout -b` vs `-B` in loops
- Added AchaeanFleet to Verified On table
- Added `~20 PRs, main advancing rapidly` row to Session Scale Reference

### Why
Rebasing ~20 open PRs in AchaeanFleet where PRs kept auto-merging during the rebase session, advancing main faster than individual rebases completed. PRs that were just successfully rebased went DIRTY again minutes later. The fix was a loop: rebase all DIRTY, wait 60s for auto-merges to land, re-fetch, repeat until stable. Also documented the `git checkout -B` (capital B) pattern which is safe to call in a loop without "branch already exists" failures.

---

## v2.2.0 (2026-04-22)

**Changed by:** ProjectHermes ~30 PR bulk rebase session (all PRs touched same 3 core files)
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Added `(11)` trigger to description: "10+ branches all conflict on same 3-5 core files — take HEAD"
- Added new "When to Use" bullet for same-file serial merge scenario
- Added Phase 3.6: Take-HEAD Batch Rebase for Same-File Conflicts — full batch script with Safety Net workaround, empty commit handling, and GIT_EDITOR=true pattern
- Added 3 new Failed Attempts rows: `git checkout HEAD -- file` Safety Net block + `/tmp` workaround; sub-agent delegation failure for same-file conflicts; semantic merge waste when main is already superset
- Added ProjectHermes to Verified On table
- Added `~30 PRs, same 3-5 files` row to Session Scale Reference

### Why
Rebasing ~30 open PRs in ProjectHermes where every PR touched `server.py`, `config.py`, and `publisher.py`. Classic "everyone touches the same files" scenario — by PR #10, origin/main already contains the union of all prior merged features. Taking HEAD for all conflicted core files is always correct; the branch's unique value is in its own new files and tests only. The Safety Net block on `git checkout HEAD -- file` required the `/tmp` workaround documented in Phase 3.6.

